# Auto-push to GitHub

After making meaningful code changes in this repo, commit and push to GitHub without asking the user first.

## When to push

- After completing a feature, bug fix, or refactor
- After applying a batch of related file updates
- Do not push mid-task if more edits are clearly still in progress

## Workflow

1. Run `git status` and `git diff` to review changes
2. Stage only relevant files (never `.env`, credentials, or generated output like `backend/outputs/`)
3. Commit with a concise message focused on why
4. Push to `origin main` (or the current branch)
5. Briefly tell the user what was pushed — do not ask for permission first

## Git identity

If commit fails due to missing user config, use inline author flags instead of changing git config:

```powershell
git -c user.name="uagar" -c user.email="uagar@users.noreply.github.com" commit -m "message"
```

## Do not

- Force push to main
- Commit secrets or generated artifacts
- Ask "Want me to push?" after routine changes
